post_text: Hello All! In an effort to accommodate instruction of all special areas in the elementary we are shifting cycle days a bit. Please note that the Cycle day #s do not go in sequential order, but rather skip around a bit to ensure equity with art, music and computer instruction. These cycle days will also be posted on our website calendar and communicated by teachers in their Google Classrooms. This change impacts elementary students but will not change anything for Jr./Sr. High students. Thank you for your patience as we work to reopen our school!

Attention Elementary Families!

Thursday, September 3rd and Friday, September 4th our elementary teachers will be scheduling Meet and Greet appointments for our students and their families. Teachers will connect with you or you may call the Elementary Office to schedule for a time slot between 8:00 a.m. and 3:00 p.m.
Please note- parents may not enter the building; however, students will be premitted to accompany their teacher to their new classrooms for a quick tour! In addition, Chromebooks will be distributed to elementary students at this time so that all students are ready for the first day of school - Tuesday, September 8th! Parents are asked to bring any school forms with them at this time.
All visitors must wear masks and follow required building safety protocols.
We look forward to seeing you again!
#phcsdpantherpride

REMINDER -In an effort to devise a thoughtful reopening plan that takes into consideration input from the PHCS Reopening Task Force, we have requested a filing deadline extension with the State until next Friday, August 7th, for submission of our reopening plan. Our primary goal is the safe return of students and staff. The completed plan will be explained through a community Zoom presentation at 6 PM on Thursday, August 6th, which will include a question and answer session. The State is permitting school reopening plans to be “living documents”. This means that plans can be adjusted in response to the impact of Coronavirus in our region.

Community members may join the presentation using this link.

Thank you all so much in advance!!

post_text:
CONGRATS PHCS Atheletes!

NYSPHSAA has announced PHCS as a 2019-2020 Scholar-Athlete School of Distinction!
Dr. Robert Zayas, NYSPHSAA Executive Director stated,
“We are excited once again to see the numbers of schools honored increase and it is a true testament to
the kind of student-athletes we were have here in New York State. We continue to be proud of this program which highlights and celebrates schools that value the importance of academics, as well as athletics. The fact that so many student-athletes thrived in the face of a pandemic this past winter is truly remarkable.”
Schools are recognized with School of Distinction status by having 100% of its varsity teams qualify for and receive
the Scholar-Athlete team award during their respective sports seasons. For the 2019-20 school year the School of Distinction winners were based on fall 2019 and winter 2020 Scholar-Athlete submissions because the spring 2020 program was cancelled.

post_text:
The PHCS Panther Paws Program, in collaboration with PARC, The People's Project, AFT, and NYSUT, will be hosting Community Days at the Parishville Beach where families can grab a free lunch and book served out of the yellow Snack Shack across from the soccer fields. These meals will be sponsored and served by the following generous community partners on:

July 28 Parishville-Hopkinton Teachers Association (books also available)
July 31 First Baptist Church of Parishville
August 14 Hopkinton-Fort Jackson Fire Department (books also available)
August 28 Ladies Auxiliary of the Parishville Fire Department

Each day, grab-and-go food will be served from 11a-1p or until food runs out. So please come out for a free meal and book, and to thank your local community partners for donating their time and resources to bring this wonderful opportunity to our community. We ask that everyone please follow social distancing and wear a mask. For more information, or if you have any questions, please email April Fullerton at afullerton@phcsd.org. We hope you enjoy!

PLEASE TAKE NOTICE that a Public Hearing will be held at the Parishville-Hopkinton Central School District on Monday, July 6, 2020, at 6:30 p.m. in the Cafeteria prior to the scheduled Reorganizational/Regular Board meeting, for the purpose of reviewing the District’s Code of Conduct and Plain Language Summary, pursuant to Chapter 181 of the Laws of 2000 and Sections 2801 and 2802 of the Education Law of the State of New York.

Due to an abundance of caution with regard to the spread of COVID-19, the public is cordially invited to attend the meeting, with a maximum capacity of twenty-five persons, which will be recorded and later uploaded to the District website (www.phcsd.org).

Thank you,
Mr.Coffin

HELLO ALL-
We are still scheduled to have our senior in-person commencement on Saturday, JUNE 27TH at 11:30 a.m.
Mr. Coffin and Mr. Engstrom have got a great start on the stage for our graduates!

post_text: The Parishville-Hopkinton Backpack Program would like to thank the AmVets Post 265 for their generous donation to our backpack program! Pictured here from left to right PHCS Superintendent, Dr. William Collins, AmVets Post 265 Commander, Frank Perry, AmVets Post 265 Finance Officer, Milton DeGraw, PHCS Backpack Committee Member,Therese Baxter. The Backpack Program could not exist without contributions such as this from our community. We are so grateful for their kindness in hosting an Italian Night Dinner to raise not only funds, but awareness to the Backpack Program. Again, thank you for your commitment to the students in our school and our community, you have made a difference in so many lives, and are helping us to maintain the Backpack Program throughout the summer months.

post_text: On June 7th, Governor Cuomo announced he will issue an Executive Order extending the deadline for school districts to receive school budget and BOE election ballots. To be counted, ballots can be accepted by hand delivery through 5pm on June 9th and received by mail until 5pm June 16th by the school district. Sealed ballot envelopes must be signed in order to be counted. These envelopes will remain sealed until after 5pm June 16th. We will share any relevant additional details once the Executive Order is released.

post_text: It has come to our attention that some voters have questions surrounding absentee ballots, specifically regarding concerns over the privacy of their vote and others finding out how they voted. Because the absentee ballot envelopes contain the name of each voter, others could link the individual voter to the vote. Please be assured, an envelope containing a returned absentee ballot is not to be opened until a determination is made that there is no reason for rejecting the ballot, which could happen if, for example, the voter fails to provide the signature required by law to appear on the envelope containing the ballot. Once such a determination is made and the envelope opened, the ballot is withdrawn without unfolding and deposited into the proper ballot box. As a result, at the time of counting, the ballots will not be linked to the envelope in which they were returned. As a kind reminder, please submit your absentee ballots to the District Office by 5:00 P.M. on June 9th. Thank you.

The 2020-2021 School Budget Vote & Board Candidate Ballots went out today! Check for your absentee ballot in the mail this week. If you are a qualified voter* and did not receive a ballot, if you need additional ballots, or if you received a ballot in error, please contact the District Office at (315) 265-4642, ext. 24402.

Please read through the Budget Newsletter (https://4.files.edl.io/d76c/05/28/20/122459-9ee63e59-cbc5-407a-a0a8-aba373969205.pdf) for more information on the proposed budget, and stay tuned for the Budget Hearing!

*A qualified voter must be a citizen of the United States, at least 18 years of age, a resident of the school district for at least 30 days, and must not be prohibited from voting under the provisions of section 5-106 of the Election Law (i.e., having been convicted of a felony or adjudged mentally incompetent).

With the ’20-‘21 school year right around the corner, we have activated our Online Pre-Registration through Schooltool.

Please use the link below to pre-register any new students to the district. This includes new students joining us for Universal Pre-K, former Head Start students who will begin Kindergarten in September 2020, and/or any students (UPK, Kindergarten-12th Grade) NEW to the PHCS district for the year. * Please note, if your child attended UPK with Mrs. Wilkes during the ’19-’20 school year, there is no need to pre-register for Kindergarten.

https://schooltool5.neric.org/SchoolTool_PARI/OnlinePreRegistration/

If you have any questions you can email Mrs. Gallagher at bgallagher@phcsd.org or call the Elementary Office @ 315-265-4642

Good Afternoon PHCS Students and Families,

Governor Cuomo just announced that all New York school buildings will remain closed for the remainder of this academic year. The Governor was asked about a timeline for re-opening schools for the next academic year and he reported that it is too early to make that decision because it will be dependent upon the COVID-19 situation at that time.

We will continue to keep you updated as additional information becomes available.

Stay safe, stay strong and we will get through this COVID-19 situation together,

Dr. C

post_text:
~ MEAL DELIVERY UPDATE FROM PHCS ~ Beginning on Monday, March 30th, PHCS food delivery will begin a Monday-Wednesday-Friday (2-2-1) delivery cycle. Two days' worth of breakfasts and two day's worth of lunches will be delivered on Mondays and Wednesdays. One day's worth of meals will be delivered on Fridays. The fewer the frequency of deliveries, the fewer interactions, the fewer interactions, the fewer the opportunities to contract the Coronavirus. This change does not alter the number of meals delivered per week or the start time of the delivery runs.

If you have not yet signed up for meal deliveries, you can find the sign-up link under the COVID-19 tab on the school's website phcsd.org.

Thank you.

post_text: We are excited to present our pilot episode of our Elementary Newscast! We hope you enjoy the production work of some our 6th graders. When we return to school the video will be shared at an assembly and a naming contest for our news show will take place prior to our next episode! A huge thank you to Mrs. Lori White and Mrs. Dayle Payne for their efforts to support our students with this project!
